ATTENTION: The school district will provide meals to students who are enrolled in online/virtual instruction. Distribution will be as follows:

Location - Meals can be picked up daily during the week between 10:30am - 11:30am at the elementary entrance.

Someone must be present to receive the meals. Meals will consist of: (1) lunch, and (1) non-perishable breakfast the next day. Portions may need to be refrigerated upon pick up. Please use the following instructions for signing up for this service:

1. Parents of elementary students ‚Äì Call the elementary office today (8/31/20) to let officials know (1) how many EL students you have for the food service.

2. Parents of JH/HS students ‚Äì Call the high school office today (8/31/20) to let officials know (1) how many JH/HS students you have for the food service.

post_text:
WILL THE DISTRICT PROVIDE TRANSPORTATION?

1) Yes. District transportation will be provided.

2) Buses are the most difficult areas to maintain social distancing.

3) We ask that parents consider bringing their children to school if possible.

4) Buses will be cleaned between routes and fogged daily.

5) Students will have assigned bus seats.

6) Students living in the same house will be seated together.

7) Students will be prohibited from riding home on a bus other than their own. Please speak with your building administrator if you have questions.

post_text:
ATTENTION: Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Open House will be different this year. Face-to-face will only be for students transitioning into Pre-K, Kindergarten, 6th grade, and students new to Bismarck R-5.

Please see the below graphic for important information concerning how it will work. In addition, please be mindful of the following guidelines put in place to reduce the number of visitors in the building at a given time:

1. We ask that students with last names starting with A-F attend from 5:30 pm - 6:30 pm.

2. We ask that students with last names starting with G-Z attend from 6:30 pm - 7:30 pm.

3. If accompanying your child to Open House, we are requesting that only ONE (1) parent attend with each child. This will allow us to reduce the number of visitors in the building at one time.

Thank you for doing your part to keep our building, students, and staff safe. Please reach out to your building administrator with any questions you might have.

post_text:
We're excited to announce that Bismarck R-5 will be able to use some Title funding to purchase basic school supplies for students in Grades PreK-5 for the upcoming 2020-2021 school year.

We have purchased enough supplies for every student in grades PreK-5. Supplies purchased for the program include paper, pencils, colored pencils, erasers, crayons, markers, dry erase markers, scissors and glue.

Please note that parents will need to purchase other school necessities, but it is our hope that this will lessen the burden on Bismarck R-5 families as it relates to basic school supplies.

post_text:
Hello everyone in the Bismarck community,

If you are still interested in getting a yearbook for 2019-2020, you will need to order it online using the following steps:

1. Go to jostens.com
2. Once there, select our school (Bismarck High School - MO) in the dark blue bar at the top of the page.
3. Click the icon that says "Shop the Collection"
4. Once the page changes to the Jostens Bismarck page, select 2020 yearbook.
5. It will take you to a page marked "Yearbook Products", click Order Now.
6. From there, it will take you to a white screen where you can fill out the information form and pay online.

The price for the book will be $30.

Please let me know if you have any questions or problems with the system. Email me at npruett@bismarckr5.org. This is the yearbook for junior high and high school students only.

Thanks!!

Mr. Pruett

post_text:
Starting Friday night on April 10th, Bismarck will be joining schools around the country by turning on our baseball field lights on Friday nights at 8:20 p.m., which is 20:20 military time, and leaving them lit for 20 minutes, and 20 seconds to honor the class of 2020. We want all community members to be aware in the event someone is wondering why our field lights are on.

At 8:20 p.m. on Friday nights look toward BHS to see the glow of our support for our graduating class of 2020.

Please, continue to follow CDC guidance and stay safe and healthy. We miss all of our students and staff.

Bismarck Administration and Staff

My life long retail friend, Eddie Wakefield, from Mike‚Äôs Market and I have been waiting to announce the Leroy Wakefield Memorial Scholarship. This is in honor of Eddie‚Äôs father. We decided to go ahead and pay it this year. We couldn‚Äôt imagine not being able to finish your senior year. The scholarship will include a 500 word essay on serving others for seniors at Bismarck High School. We have talked to superintendent Jason King and decided to have a May 1st deadline for this essay and the scholarship will be for $1000. We‚Äôre trying to do our part in these difficult times to shine a little light around the area.

post_text:
We have received a lot of great questions concerning the Educational Resource website we have established to keep academic learning going during the closure. Here is some additional information:

1. Books - We will be directing students to take their books home.

2. Grades - These optional resources will not count for or against grades.

3. Materials - Essential materials posted in the resources website will be covered in class again once school resumes.

4. Internet Access - We realize not everyone has internet access, which is why all of the posted resources are optional.

5. Slow Internet - Most of the resources will be small documents, which should hopefully download even with slow internet connections.

6. Drive Access - A Google Drive account is not needed to view the resources website. Anyone with internet can access the website.

https://drive.google.com/drive/u/2/folders/1XE0l0F1XA8P5FM0i6UJwALaByjVqFOtf

Bismarck R5 JR/SR High School Counseling
February 28 at 8:25 AM ¬∑

Mackenzie Bowen has been selected for our Elks Teen of the Month for March. Mackenzie's school-related awards include 2nd place at the Mineral Area College Art Show and Principal's Honor Roll. Mackenzie has been a member of the National Honor Society since 2017 and Pep Club since 2014. Mackenzie's other activities include A+ tutoring, raising money for Project Graduation, working at a daycare, and babysitting. Mackenzie plans on attending Missouri Western State University to pursue a career as a pediatric nurse. Way to go Mackenzie! We are so proud of you!
#bismarckrising

post_text:
JH Bismarck Baseball

March 2, 2020 through March 6, 2020 will be the days set aside for JH Bismarck Baseball tryouts. Players will be notified whether they have made the team during this week of practice.

Players need to have a physical.

Players should bring clothes to practice inside and outside. If it is nice outside, we will be outside. If it is too cold or rainy, we will be inside somewhere. Please dress in layers for outside. Bring baseball equipment for practicing.

Practice is from 3:20-4:45 every day.

February 22 at 4:42 PM ¬∑

As our season comes to an end today I just wanted to post about how proud I am of my girls. They‚Äôve done things that no one else wanted to do and that‚Äôs show up. Playing varsity basketball is a big commitment. They dedicated their time to play basketball this season, and in my opinion that speaks volumes. I‚Äôve seen a lot of improvement throughout our season, but basketball is not only about wins and losses. It‚Äôs about teamwork, responsibility, honesty, respect, dedication, integrity and so much more. I can honestly say that I have a great group of girls who continue to make me proud to be their coach. Each one of these girls holds a special place in my heart and I‚Äôm so very proud of them!

ATTENTION JH/HS FAMILIES: Student Led Conferences will be held February 27th from 5:30-7:00. Not only will you get to look through your child's portfolio for this semester, but you will also get to be a part of scheduling for the 2020-21 school year. There will also be an informational meeting for A+ and Upward Bound will be in attendance to answer any questions. Please see the flyer for more details.

*In regards to scheduling, we are doing something new this year, and student schedules will not be accepted by Mr. Reeves, the counselor, until they have been approved by a parent/guardian. PTC night will be the first opportunity for parents to sign off on their child's schedule(s) and those schedules will be processed first.

EVERY STUDENT WHO WILL BE 18 YEARS OF AGE BY 11/3/20 CAN REGISTER TO VOTE ON FRIDAY, 2/7/20!
Voter Registration will be in the New Commons on 2/7/20 from 10:30 a.m. ‚Äì Noon.

Be sure to have the last 4 digits of your social security number, and bring your driver‚Äôs license, if you have one.

The League of Women Voters is a non-partisan organization dedicated to our democracy for the past 100 years.

Congratulations for reaching this very significant milestone in your life! You are the future of our country!
